[size=14pt][b]THE BIG CHANGE: DUAL-LANE MINING (v10.3.5)[/b][/size]

We've fundamentally changed how mining works on Q-NarwhalKnight. Instead of one mining algorithm where GPUs dominate, we now have [b]two parallel lanes[/b] with a 50/50 reward split:

[table]
[tr][td][b]Lane[/b][/td][td][b]Algorithm[/b][/td][td][b]Hardware[/b][/td][td][b]Reward Share[/b][/td][/tr]
[tr][td]GPU Lane[/td][td]Massively parallel BLAKE3 hashing[/td][td]OpenCL (AMD + NVIDIA)[/td][td]50%[/td][/tr]
[tr][td]CPU VDF Lane[/td][td]BLAKE3 × 4,300 sequential iterations[/td][td]Any CPU[/td][td]50%[/td][/tr]
[/table]

[b]Why this matters:[/b] The VDF (Verifiable Delay Function) lane is [i]inherently sequential[/i] — you cannot parallelize it. A $50,000 GPU farm has zero advantage over a $200 laptop on this lane. This means:

[list]
[li][b]CPU-only miners earn 50% of block rewards[/b] without owning a GPU[/li]
[li]GPU miners still earn their 50% through the BLAKE3 parallel lane[/li]
[li]Both lanes run simultaneously — you don't choose, you mine both[/li]
[li]VDF performance: ~200μs per doubling with Montgomery-integrated optimization[/li]
[/list]

[b]Difficulty adjustment[/b] now uses LWMA (Linear Weighted Moving Average) — adjusts per-block for stable 1-second block times. No more difficulty spikes or troughs.

