[size=14pt][b]THE DAG BLOCK RECOVERY STORY[/b][/size]

A bug in how RocksDB stores blocks caused 545,710 blocks to become invisible. They weren't deleted — they were stored under a different key format ([tt]qblock:dag:{height}:{proposer}[/tt] instead of [tt]qblock:height:{N}[/tt]). When syncing nodes asked for block ranges, the scan missed these entries due to string-sort ordering.

The fix adds a fallback read path: if a block isn't found at its height key, the system scans for DAG-format keys at that height. All 545K blocks are now visible and sync correctly. 10 unit tests verify the fix.

No data was ever lost. The blocks were always there — just hiding in plain sight.

[size=14pt][b]BALANCE INTEGRITY FIX[/b][/size]

We discovered three independent code paths that write balance updates:
[list=1]
[li][b]Block processing[/b] (normal operation) — already had dedup[/li]
[li][b]P2P gossipsub[/b] (peer propagation) — was using volatile LRU cache[/li]
[li][b]Catch-up processing[/b] (restart/sync) — had NO dedup[/li]
[/list]

On node restart, paths 2 and 3 would re-credit balances that were already applied. The fix: persistent RocksDB flags ([tt]processed_balance_block:{hash}[/tt]) in all three paths. Balance updates are now idempotent regardless of restarts, resyncs, or P2P retransmissions.

[size=14pt][b]FPGA & ASIC DEVELOPMENT[/b][/size]

We're actively developing hardware acceleration for the mining algorithm:

[list]
[li][b]QUG-V1 FPGA RTL[/b] (SystemVerilog) updated for dual-lane mining[/li]
[li]SHA-3 Keccak-f[1600] hardware core added (26-cycle per hash)[/li]
[li]VDF depth increased from 127 to 16,383 iterations (14-bit counter)[/li]
[li]LWMA difficulty awareness with hardware leading-zero counter[/li]
[li]Autonomous nonce-scanning mining controller[/li]
[li]Genus-2 VDF field operations (mod_sub_256, configurable modulus)[/li]
[li]All fits within 10% of Kintex-7 XC7K325T resources[/li]
[/list]

We're in discussions with FPGA manufacturers for a 12nm box miner design at $149 target price point, offering 6-10x advantage over CPU mining on the VDF lane.

